<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is SRM in brewing?", answer: "SRM stands for Standard Reference Method, an American measure of beer color. It is determined by measuring the absorbance of light passing through a sample at 430 nanometers in a half-inch path-length cell, multiplied by 12.7. The SRM scale runs from about 2 for very pale lagers to over 40 for imperial stouts. Europeans use EBC, which equals roughly 1.97 times SRM." },
  { question: "What is the Morey equation?", answer: "The Morey equation is the most widely used homebrew formula for estimating beer color from a recipe. It calculates Malt Color Units (MCU) as the sum of each malt weight times its lovibond rating divided by batch volume in gallons, then takes 1.4922 times MCU raised to the power of 0.6859. Morey is favored over older linear formulas because it accounts for the fact that adding more dark malt produces diminishing returns in color." },
  { question: "How accurate is calculated SRM?", answer: "Calculated SRM is a useful estimate but reality varies because the boil time, kettle caramelization, water chemistry, fermentation, and yeast strain all influence final beer color. Most brewing software gets within 2 to 3 SRM points of measured values for typical beers and within 5 SRM points for very dark beers. Use the calculator to choose between recipes and styles, not as a substitute for measuring the finished beer." },
  { question: "What is a Lovibond rating?", answer: "Lovibond is the traditional unit for malt color, named after Joseph Williams Lovibond who developed the original colored-glass comparator in 1883. A 2°L pale malt is the lightest color base malt and a 600°L black patent malt is the darkest. Modern malt analyses report Lovibond and SRM almost interchangeably for individual malts, with the conversion being approximately SRM equals 1.3546 times Lovibond minus 0.76." },
  { question: "What SRM is a stout?", answer: "Dry stouts and most American stouts fall between 25 and 40 SRM. Imperial stouts and Russian imperial stouts run 30 to 40+ and appear opaque black in the glass. Schwarzbier (German black lager) sits at 17 to 30 SRM but reads as black at typical glass thicknesses because of the iron-related compounds in the dark malts." }
]) %>

