    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>Beer Color and the SRM Scale</h2>
      <p>
        The Standard Reference Method, or SRM, is the American beer color scale used by the Brewers Association and BJCP guidelines. It is determined by measuring the absorbance of light at 430 nanometers passing through a half-inch sample, multiplied by 12.7. The result is a scale where 2 is straw yellow, 10 is amber, 20 is copper-brown, and 40 plus is opaque black. European brewers use the EBC scale instead, which is roughly twice the SRM number, so a 6 SRM pilsner is about 12 EBC. Both scales report the same physical property in different units.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>How the Morey Equation Works</h2>
      <p>
        Daniel Morey's 1995 equation is the most widely used homebrew color model. The first step is calculating Malt Color Units, which is the sum of each malt weight in pounds times its color in degrees Lovibond, divided by the batch volume in gallons. The second step transforms MCU into SRM with the formula 1.4922 times MCU raised to the power 0.6859. The exponent is critical because it captures the diminishing-returns nature of dark malt: doubling the dark malt does not double the visible color. Older linear models like Daniels overestimate dark beer color because they ignore this saturation effect.
      </p>

      <h2>Choosing Malts for a Target Color</h2>
      <p>
        Base malts contribute most of the grist weight but very little color, ranging from 1.5 to 4 degrees Lovibond for pilsner and pale base malts and up to 10 degrees for Munich and Vienna. Crystal and caramel malts in the 40 to 120 Lovibond range contribute most of the color in amber, brown, and red ales while also adding caramel sweetness and body. Roasted malts like chocolate malt at 350 to 450 degrees Lovibond and black patent at 500 to 600 degrees provide the dark color of porters and stouts in small quantities. Use crystal for warm reds and ambers and use roasted malt for cool browns and blacks.
      </p>

      <h2>Why Calculated Color Differs From Reality</h2>
      <p>
        The Morey equation is a model and the actual finished beer color depends on many factors the formula cannot account for. Long boils caramelize wort sugars and shift the color toward red and brown. Hard water and high pH increase the extraction of dark color compounds from the husks. Open versus closed fermenters and wort oxidation in transfer can also shift color. As a rule of thumb, expect calculated SRM to land within 2 to 3 points of measured values for pale and amber beers and within 5 points for dark beers. The calculator is a planning tool, not a substitute for visual judgment.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>What is SRM in brewing?</h3>
      <p>
        SRM is the Standard Reference Method beer color scale, measured by the absorbance of light at 430 nm. Pale lagers sit at 2 to 4 SRM, ambers at 10 to 18, and stouts above 30. EBC is the European equivalent and roughly equals 2 times SRM.
      </p>

      <h3>What is the Morey equation?</h3>
      <p>
        Morey calculates SRM as 1.4922 times Malt Color Units raised to 0.6859. MCU is the sum of weight in pounds times Lovibond color, divided by gallons. The non-linear exponent captures the diminishing-returns effect of dark malts.
      </p>

      <h3>How accurate is calculated SRM?</h3>
      <p>
        Calculated SRM is usually within 2 to 3 points of measured for pale and amber beers and within 5 points for very dark beers. Boil duration, kettle caramelization, and water chemistry all shift the actual color away from prediction.
      </p>

      <h3>What does Lovibond mean?</h3>
      <p>
        Lovibond is the traditional malt color rating, named after Joseph Williams Lovibond's 1883 colored-glass comparator. SRM equals approximately 1.3546 times Lovibond minus 0.76 for individual malts, and most modern maltsters report both numbers on a malt analysis sheet.
      </p>

      <h3>What SRM is a typical IPA?</h3>
      <p>
        American IPAs sit at 6 to 14 SRM (gold to deep gold) and English IPAs at 8 to 14 SRM (gold to amber). Hazy New England IPAs typically come in lighter and yellower because of less crystal malt and lower attenuation.
      </p>

